    <title>Combined summary - [BIP proposal] Private Payments</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T22:19:49.475708+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-July/020623.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Several proposals and updates have been suggested to improve the Bitcoin ecosystem. One proposal is to use bech32 instead of base58 for more compact QR codes, which has been agreed upon. Additionally, there have been discussions around third-party services offering to publish OP_RETURN notification payloads in the blockchain for a fee paid over Lightning Network without linking the notifier's identity to their wallet, potentially offering a privacy boost. Anti-spam measures can be built into payment codes by demanding that a notification transaction meets some minimum miner fee or a multiple of some trailing average.The bitcoin-dev mailing list has been discussing proposals to improve the limitations of the BIP47 standard. The proposed new payment code structure would allocate a 2-byte bitflag array that signals address and script types that the receiver is deriving, with notification transactions still existing but no longer leaving a privacy footprint on the blockchain.One concern raised was the potential issues that may arise if the number of standard scripts increases significantly, which could create a performance hit. One solution is using address type flags to solve these issues at the expense of having extra bytes. Damian James Williamson questioned the legibility of the blockchain and the fungibility of UTXOs in a proposal, which was responded to by KING JAMES HRMH stating that the blockchain must be legible for it to be an indelible record, and that Bitcoin is only fungible because it uses the blockchain.Another suggestion was to require an OP_RETURN burn instead of sending coins back to miners. In another discussion, it was proposed that notification transactions should no longer leave a footprint on the blockchain and instead just be a single OP_RETURN containing a value that only Alice and Bob can calculate. Alternatively, Alice could publish on a Tor hidden service that other wallets check. However, there were concerns about the accessibility of data on-chain and guaranteeing their availability when restoring from backup.Overall, these discussions highlight ongoing efforts to improve privacy and efficiency within the Bitcoin ecosystem through various technical solutions and proposals.</summary>
